>>>> Hey Jared,

>>>> See below - I left your original question/my answers in this email, but
>>>> also addressing the MDR pricing question here:
>>>>
>>>> So, we definitely have the ability to price an MDR. I think what's its
>>>> important is that the MDR pricing model should be targeted to specific
>>>> merchants.
>>>>
>>>> For instance, merchants that have a very low average ticket.
>>>>
>>>> For your example: YES, you can lock in a specific MDR. So you can go in
>>>> at 80 bps for a merchant. We would just take the merchant’s total
>>>> monthly volume and multiple by the MDR to arrive at the revenue owed to
>>>> Shift.
>>>>
>>>> Example:
>>>>
>>>> Merchant does $10M in sales volume
>>>> MDR is locked in at .0080 or 80 bps.
>>>>
>>>> $10,000,000 x .0080 = $80,000 owed to Shift4.
>>>>
>>>>
>>>> Now, to the question about how low can you go. I
>>>> did some research and put this together for you. In
>>>> our history of the MDR pricing model, the
>>>> average/typical merchant we targeted had an
>>>> average ticket of roughly $10-$15, and would pay an
>>>> MDR of .001 0 (1 0 bps)
>>>>
>>>> The math works out to an average cost of about 2-
>>>> 2.1%.
>>>> Avg Ticket - $12.50
>>>> Avg Costs (variable) = .26 + .085 = .345.
>>>> Avg MDR = .0010 (or $12.50 x .0010 = $.0125)
>>>>
>>>> Avg Revenue = $.3575.
>>>>
>>>> So in this example, the MDR is roughly 3.5% of the
>>>> total Revenue to Shift
>>>>
>>>>
>>>>
>>>>
>>>>
>>>>
>>>>
>>>>
>>>> On the other hand, if we did this same 10 bps MDR for
>>>> a merchant that had an avg ticket of $125.00
>>>>
>>>> Avg Ticket - $125.00
>>>> Avg Costs (variable) = .26 + .085 = 1.3975.
>>>> Avg MDR = .0010 (or $125.00 x .0010 = $.125)
>>>>
>>>> The MDR in this example would be around 9% of the
>>>> total Revenue to Shift.
>>>>
